text:
Sorry I repeated this so much during stream, but here's a few things you should know in order to ramp up the style of your gameplay

1. Remap your controls, when in comes to nero and V, their attack rely heavily on charging their shots, so having it on your triggers or bumpers lets you press melee while charging griffon or blue rose. If you're experienced with whats called claw grip or claw control, you don't have to, but to most it's preferable

2. taunt whenever there's an opening, like when you're at distance or in the air. Air taunts will do certain things like retain height and knock enemies.
3. Many of the mechanics in this game require good timing, so I'll break this down into seperate parts.

A. When it comes to nero, there are two things that require precise timing, exceed and dodging. Ex act is when you rev your sword a little after the swing is supposed to have active damage frames (LT after an attack lands). Max act is on a few frames, which is difficult to nail but you know you've done it if it's a little earlier than ex act frames (LT IMMEDIATELY after the attack lands). Some of this logic doesn't apply to other moves like roulette spin so experiment yourself. Tabble hopping with nero requires you to roll (RB - X sideways of target) when the attack lands on you, which is risky but scores style (and a little something you'll get later). The dashes are just pressing X in a direction afterwards

B. With V, you can actually teleport to another enemy immediately after an execution. Just target the other enemy that's downed (RB) and press B after you've killed your enemy but still in the animation

C. with dante, royal guard is the power move. similar to nero, when an attack lands on you, you press B in royal guard style (down on dpad) and it will completely negate damage and even charge dt and style. If you hold block, it drains dt and if you have none left you get staggered trying to block

D. Enemy step has a unique "tech"  called jump cancelling. Any (or at least most) animation(s) like gunshots, melee attacks, and even taunts can be cancelled with a jump. This is where enemy step comes in, you can jump off an enemies hitbox, allowing you to reset you double jumps, and initiate another attack. This is how the infamous SWORD TRICK SWORD TRICK was born, as they could jump cancel a dash into an enemy, follow with an attack and immediately dash again.

E. Parrying, if your weapon's attack is about to clash with another enemies' weapon, you can actually parry, this is especially useful on a later boss you'll fight. The best moves to do this with are moves that strike downwards, lift enemies or strike directly infront of you (even V)

4. With dante, if you struggle with switching styles on the fly that's fine, you can just experiment with one and get experience with one at a time and that's fine. Starting with swordmaster is the best since it gives you extra moves with you melee weapons. Trickster is also another good one, since it gives you invincibility frames during the dash.

5. Finally, the void. Experiment as much as you want, any enemy except bosses and world spawned enemies can be fought there, and in the options menu you can get infinite DT, change enemies and make enemies attack, which is helpful in practicing combos in combat and timing on many moves.

I don't know if you'll take most of the advice here, but no matter what I want you to enjoy the game, and if you take it at your own pace that's fine. This is just for if you want to take a step into the intricacies of the game and want to improve your experience, because trust me and the rest of the DMC community it's the most fun when you get to pull off something that not only is technically impressive, but looks and feels cool.
